<p>You're browsing AI tools and come across two names: <strong>J.A.R.V.I.S.</strong> and <strong>Claude Code</strong> (or GitHub Copilot, Cursor, etc.). Both involve AI. Both help you get things done. So... which one do you need?</p>

<p>Short answer: <strong>Both. They solve different problems.</strong></p>

<p>Let's break it down.</p>

<h2>Claude Code: Your AI Pair Programmer</h2>

<p>Claude Code (and tools like it) are <strong>AI coding assistants</strong>. They sit inside your editor (VS Code, Cursor, etc.) and help you <em>write code faster</em>.</p>

<h3>What Claude Code Does Well</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Code completion:</strong> Start typing a function, and it suggests the rest. It's autocomplete on steroids.</li>
  <li><strong>Refactoring:</strong> "Convert this class to use hooks." Claude Code rewrites it for you.</li>
  <li><strong>Bug fixing:</strong> Highlight broken code, ask "what's wrong here?" and get explanations + fixes.</li>
  <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> "Write JSDoc comments for this function." Done instantly.</li>
  <li><strong>Learning:</strong> Ask questions about APIs, libraries, or patterns while you code. It's Stack Overflow, inline.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What Claude Code Doesn't Do</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Doesn't work outside your editor:</strong> It's scoped to the file you're editing. Can't browse the web, manage files, or interact with other apps.</li>
  <li><strong>Doesn't remember context across sessions:</strong> Close the editor, and it forgets your conversation. No long-term memory.</li>
  <li><strong>Doesn't act autonomously:</strong> You drive the workflow. It responds to prompts but doesn't take initiative.</li>
  <li><strong>Doesn't integrate with your life:</strong> Can't schedule tasks, monitor APIs, manage your calendar, or coordinate across machines.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Claude Code is a tool <em>you</em> use to code faster. It's reactive, scoped, and editor-bound.</strong></p>

<h2>J.A.R.V.I.S.: Your Autonomous Agent Runtime</h2>

<p>J.A.R.V.I.S. is an <strong>operating layer for AI agents</strong>. It's not tied to your editor — it runs <em>continuously</em>, across all your devices, and handles tasks far beyond code.</p>

<h3>What J.A.R.V.I.S. Does Well</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Persistent memory:</strong> Remembers everything you've told it — people, projects, preferences — across all conversations, forever.</li>
  <li><strong>Screen awareness:</strong> Sees what you're doing (with permission), detects struggles, and offers proactive help.</li>
  <li><strong>Multi-machine control:</strong> Acts across your laptop, desktop, and servers as one unified environment.</li>
  <li><strong>Browser automation:</strong> Navigates websites, fills forms, scrapes data, monitors pages.</li>
  <li><strong>Desktop control:</strong> Interacts with native apps (Spotify, Excel, Slack) on Windows, macOS, or Linux.</li>
  <li><strong>Delegation:</strong> Spawns specialist agents (researchers, writers, analysts) to handle complex tasks in parallel.</li>
  <li><strong>Goal-driven execution:</strong> Set an OKR, and J.A.R.V.I.S. breaks it into tasks, tracks progress, and autonomously executes.</li>
  <li><strong>Always-on operation:</strong> Runs 24/7, handling scheduled tasks, monitoring alerts, and responding to events.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What J.A.R.V.I.S. Doesn't Do (Out of the Box)</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Inline code completion:</strong> It can <em>write</em> code (by spawning a Software Engineer agent), but it's not optimized for real-time, keystroke-level autocomplete.</li>
  <li><strong>Editor integration:</strong> It doesn't live inside VS Code. (You could build a plugin, but that's on you.)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>J.A.R.V.I.S. is an agent <em>that runs your life</em>. It's proactive, persistent, and environment-aware.</strong></p>

